observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Chairperson of the Inventory Committee:
Prepare and submit to the Municipal Mayor for his approval, a Physical Inventory Plan (PIP) indicating therein the specific assignments/duties of the Committee members, cut-off date and schedule specifying the dates and locations of the inventory taking activities from start up to the targeted completion of the physical inventory;
Conduct the physical inventory within the period identified in the PIP and tag all counted properties of the Municipality;
Prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) within 60 days from the completion of the physical inventory and furnish a copy of the report to the COA Team Leader, Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer.
We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer conduct a reconciliation of the PPE included in the RPCPPE with the recorded properties in the books of accounts of the municipality and prepare the necessary report on the results of the reconciliation to the Municipal Mayor for his/her appropriate action, in cases of non-existing/missing properties, if any. Also, record in the books of accounts those items found during the count but were not yet recorded in the books.
We recommended finally that the Municipal Mayor, together with the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer, perform the procedures to account for non-existing/missing properties as a result of the reconciliation conducted to facilitate the disposition of these items in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2020-006 to reflect a reliable balance of the PPE account in the Financial Statement.

We recommended that the Municipal Assessor:
Conduct physical surveys to verify and determine whether all real properties within the Municipality are properly listed in the assessment rolls;
Conduct vigorous Tax Mapping activities in order to resolve issues on duplicate Tax Declarations;
undertake appraisal and general revision of real property assessments every three (3) years as required in Section 219 of RA 7160 in order to come up with a reliable amount of assessment on real property taxes;
update and reconcile all records pertaining to real properties within the Municipality and its owners.
We also recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
update the Taxpayer’s Index Card and reconcile the same with the records of the Municipal Assessors;
submit the Taxpayer’s Index Card to the Municipal Accountant at the start of each year as basis in recording RPT Receivables;
actively implement tax collection methods and strategies to increase RPT collections and resolve the bloating balances of uncollected RPT in the books;
prepare a certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one (1) year including reasons for such non-collection, and;
submit such list to the Sangguniang Bayan on or before December 31 of the year immediately succeeding the year in which the delinquencies were incurred, and request for assistance from the SB in the enforcement of the remedies for collection provided in RA No. 7160.
We also recommend that the Municipal Accountant record every January of each year the full amount of RPT due and collectible as receivables based on the computed amount per RPT Tax Account Register/Taxpayer’s index cards.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
record correctly the collections from payments of Real Property Taxes, in accordance with the PPSAS prescribed accounting entries, and;
prepare the necessary accounting entries to adjust the understatement of Real Property Tax/Special Education Tax Receivable accounts and other related accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Engineer and the General Services Officer accomplish the following:
(a) complete the conduct of inventory of the LGU’s local roads;
(b) prepare an accurate Inventory of Local Roads, and;
(c) submit the Inventory of Local Roads to DILG immediately and every three years thereafter, without need for demand from the said Office.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor confirm the compliance by the Municipal Engineer and the General Services Officer with the provisions of DILG Memorandum Circular No. 2011-52 and RA No. 7160 relative to the above-enumerated specific recommendations.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
revert to the Due to BIR account the amount reclassified as Other Payables and Prior Year’s Adjustment;
identify the persons/entities to whom the amount was deducted;
remit the amount to the BIR immediately;
reconcile monthly all taxes withheld from taxpayers and the amount remitted to the BIR to avoid penalties.

We recommended that the GAD Focal Point System headed by the Municipal Mayor:
Require all Department Heads to submit their respective accomplishments on GAD related programs, projects and activities including the equivalent amount of expenditures to ensure that the LGU complied with the minimum requirement of GAD related expenditures to at least 5% of the total estimated income of the Municipality;
Submit the necessary documents to support the LGU’s annual GAD Accomplishment Report.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):
Limit the hiring of Job Order workers to indispensable functions only and pay the prescribed daily minimum wage as prescribed by the Regional Tripartite Wages and Productivity Boards for Region VIII;
Refrain from hiring Job Order Workers who have reached the compulsory retirement age;
Prioritize the hiring for vacant Plantilla Positions, subject to the prescribed PS limitation.

We recommended that the Municipal Agriculture Officer:
a.)	justify the excessive purchase of bangus feeds which were not distributed and have expired;
b.)	adhere to the regulations on procuring goods equivalent only to three-month supply and;
c.)	discontinue the distribution of the expired Bangus feeds to avoid adverse effects on the cultured bangus of the fisherfolks association.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
that the Municipal Accountant submit the names of employees whose loan amortizations were paid by the LGU but whose salaries were not deducted in the payroll; 
the Municipal Accountant to install strong internal control procedures within her Officer and assign a separate personnel for the preparation of GSIS loan remittances from the payroll preparer.
